h3. Issue Summary

Getting raw file content via the CURL command sometimes gives the old contents.

*Sample CURL command*:
{code:java}
curl -i -H "Accept: application/json" https://bitbucket.org/srstaging/raw_file_test/raw/master/raw_file.json
{code}
h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Created a new repository
# Cloned the new repo locally
# Created a JSON file named *raw_file.json* with the below contents then pushed the file in the master branch
{code:java}
{
    "test1": "some_val",
    "test2": "some_val"
}
{code}
# Ran the CURL command below and I can see the latest JSON contents
{code:java}
curl -i -H "Accept: application/json" https://bitbucket.org/srstaging/raw_file_test/raw/master/raw_file.json
{code}
# Edited the file *raw_file.json* contents and pushed it to the master branch
{code:java}
{
    "test1": "some_val",
    "test2": "some_val_edited_locally"
}
{code}
# Run the below CURL command again for 2-4 times:
{code:java}
curl -i -H "Accept: application/json" https://bitbucket.org/srstaging/raw_file_test/raw/master/raw_file.json
{code}
(!) Here, I can see that the contents show by the CURL command are inconsistent, sometimes it shows the old JSON contents but after some time, the new contents shows correctly.

h3. Expected Results
 * The new and updated version of the JSON file should update in real-time

h3. Actual Results
 * The new updates of the file should be updated in real-time

h3. Workaround

I'm currently suspecting the browser is caching the JSON file and this why it's happening.

As a workaround, adding a timestamp parameter in the JSON endpoint when running the CURL command will load the fresh JSON file every time.
{code:java}
curl -i -H "Accept: application/json" https://bitbucket.org/srstaging/raw_file_test/raw/master/raw_file.json?nocache=SOME_TIMESTAMP_HERE
{code}
[https://stackoverflow.com/a/15041641]

h3. Issue Summary

Pulling commits from pull requests through API using pagination throws an error {"type": "error", "error":

{"message": "Invalid page"}
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a repository that contains a Pull Request with over 10 commits
 # Run below command:
{code:java}
curl -X GET -u username:password https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/username/reposlug/pullrequests/PullRequestId/commits?page=1{code}

 # Note that it throws that error. If you exclude ?page=1, the command executes using as default pagelen=10 and at the end of the json it says "next......?page=8xhd".

h3. Expected Results

Running [https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/username/reposlug/pullrequests/PullRequestId/commits?page=1|https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/username/reposlug/pullrequests/2/commits?page=1] would not throw errors and would display the first page of the commits from the pull request.
h3. Actual Results

The below exception is thrown:
{noformat}
{"type": "error", "error": {"message": "Invalid page"}
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Use pagelen instead such as {{commits?pagelen=10}}.

